ğŸ“Š java 8 provide some below predefined functional interfaces in java.util.function package

What inbuilt functional interfaces have you used?

Iâ€™ve mainly used 

1ï¸âƒ£Predicate for ğŸ‘‰ filter() ,
2ï¸âƒ£Function for transformations ğŸ‘‰ map() , 
3ï¸âƒ£Consumer for processing data in ğŸ‘‰ forEach()
4ï¸âƒ£Supplier for default or lazy values,ğŸ‘‰ Use case: lazy object creation
especially while working with Java 8 streams in service layers

Consumer -Accepts one input, returns nothing
predicate -Accepts one input, returns boolean
Function -Accepts one input, returns a result
Supplier -No input, returns a result
BiConsumer -Accepts two inputs, no output
Bipredicate -Accepts two inputs, returns boolean



// Consumer example
        Consumer<String> print = s -> System.out.println(s);
        print.accept("Hello Consumer!");

// Predicate example
ğŸ—ï¸ Project usage : used Predicte in streams to filter data based on business conditions

Predicate<Integer> isPositive = n -> n > 0;
System.out.println(isPositive.test(5));  // true

// Function example
        Function<String, Integer> length = s -> s.length();
        System.out.println(length.apply("Java8"));  // 5

we use function to transform entity object into DTO's

// Supplier example
Takes no input, returns output
ğŸ—ï¸ Project usage : â€œSupplier is used for lazy object creation and default values

        Supplier<String> message = () -> "Default Value";
        System.out.println(message.get());

        // UnaryOperator example
        UnaryOperator<Integer> square = x -> x * x;
        System.out.println(square.apply(6));  // 36

        // BinaryOperator example
        BinaryOperator<Integer> add = (a, b) -> a + b;
        System.out.println(add.apply(4, 7));  // 11

        // BiConsumer example
        BiConsumer<String, Integer> printKV = (k,v) -> System.out.println(k + ": " + v);
        printKV.accept("Age", 30);

        // BiPredicate example
        BiPredicate<String, String> equalsIgnoreCase = (s1, s2) -> s1.equalsIgnoreCase(s2);
        System.out.println(equalsIgnoreCase.test("hello", "HELLO"));  // true

        // BiFunction example
        BiFunction<Integer, Integer, String> concatSum = (a, b) -> "Sum: " + (a+b);
        System.out.println(concatSum.apply(10, 20));  // Sum: 30

1ï¸âƒ£Can lambda expression throw checked exception?
âŒ NO (unless interface declares it)

@FunctionalInteface
interface Task{
    void run() throws IOException;
